1. Since `z < y`, and `z вКІ ѕИ`, the valuation must satisfy `y вКІ ѕИ`. But `hyвВВ` gives `y вК≠ ѕИ`. This directly yields `False`.

However, we need to ensure that the `Rel` relation in the frame respects the hereditary property of the valuation. 

But in the Lean formalization, the `Rel` of `Kripke2.Frame` is the same as the order `вЙ§` in the frame. Moreover, the `Satisfies` relation (i.e., `вКІ`) is defined such that if `x вЙ§ y` and `x вКІ p`, then `y вКІ p`. 

In particular, in Lean, the `Satisfies` class for `Kripke2` models has the property that if `x вЙ§ y`, then for any formula `ѕИ`, `x вКІ ѕИ вЖТ y вКІ ѕИ`. 

However, in our case, the order `x < y` is actually `x вЙЇ y`, which is the *strict* order, and it is not necessarily the case that `x вЙЇ y` implies `x вЙ§ y`. 

But, looking at the Lean definition of `Kripke2.Frame`, the `Rel` (i.e., `вЙ§`) is reflexive, and `x вЙЇ y` is defined as `x < y`, where `x < y` is `x вЙ§ y вИІ y вКѓ x`. 

But if `x вЙЇ y`, then `x вЙ§ y` (as `x вЙЇ y` implies `x < y`, which implies `x вЙ§ y`). 

Therefore, `z вЙЇ y` implies `z вЙ§ y`, and because of the hereditary property of `Satisfies`, `z вКІ ѕИ` implies `y вКІ ѕИ`. But this contradicts `y вК≠ ѕИ`.

